    {"id": "GS071", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Chemistry", "question_text": "Which of the following is NOT a chemical change?", "options": ["Burning wood", "Rusting iron", "Dissolving sugar in water", "Baking bread"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Dissolving sugar in water is a physical change — the sugar can be recovered by evaporating the water and its chemical identity doesn't change. Burning, rusting, and baking all produce new chemical substances.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS072", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Chemistry", "question_text": "The smallest unit of an element that retains the chemical properties of that element is:", "options": ["Molecule", "Compound", "Atom", "Ion"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "An atom is the smallest unit of an element that still has that element's chemical properties. A molecule is two or more atoms bonded together. An ion is a charged atom.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS073", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Physics", "question_text": "Potential energy stored due to an object's height above the ground is called:", "options": ["Kinetic energy", "Chemical energy", "Gravitational potential energy", "Thermal energy"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Gravitational potential energy is stored energy due to height (PE = mgh). As an object falls, PE converts to kinetic energy (energy of motion). Chemical energy is stored in bonds.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS074", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Physics", "question_text": "According to the law of conservation of energy:", "options": ["Energy can be created from nothing in a nuclear reaction", "Energy can be destroyed by friction", "Energy cannot be created or destroyed, only converted", "Chemical reactions always create new energy"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "The law of conservation of energy states that energy cannot be created or destroyed, only converted from one form to another. A light bulb converts electrical energy to light and heat.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS075", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "Which blood type is the universal donor?", "options": ["Type A", "Type B", "Type AB", "Type O negative"], "correct_index": 3, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Type O negative blood lacks A, B, and Rh antigens, so it can be given to anyone without triggering an immune reaction. Type AB positive is the universal recipient (can receive any type).", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS076", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "Which organ is responsible for filtering blood and producing urine?", "options": ["Liver", "Pancreas", "Kidney", "Spleen"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "The kidneys filter blood, removing waste products and excess water to produce urine. The liver detoxifies blood and produces bile. The pancreas produces insulin and digestive enzymes.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS077", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "The function of red blood cells is to:", "options": ["Fight infection", "Carry oxygen via hemoglobin", "Clot wounds", "Produce antibodies"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Red blood cells (erythrocytes) carry oxygen using hemoglobin protein. White blood cells fight infection. Platelets clot wounds. Antibodies are produced by B lymphocytes (a type of white blood cell).", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS078", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "Photosynthesis produces oxygen as a byproduct. Where does this oxygen come from?", "options": ["Carbon dioxide molecules", "Water molecules split by light energy", "Glucose breakdown", "Atmospheric nitrogen"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 3, "explanation": "During the light reactions of photosynthesis, water molecules (H2O) are split by light energy. The oxygen atoms from water are released as O2 gas — this is the origin of the oxygen we breathe.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS079", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Earth Science", "question_text": "What force causes tides on Earth?", "options": ["Earth's rotation", "Atmospheric pressure", "The Moon's gravitational pull", "Ocean currents"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Tides are caused primarily by the Moon's gravitational pull on Earth's oceans. The Sun also influences tides but to a lesser extent. Earth's rotation affects the timing of tides.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS080", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Earth Science", "question_text": "Which of the following correctly describes a food chain?", "options": ["Hawk → Snake → Mouse → Grass", "Grass → Mouse → Snake → Hawk", "Snake → Hawk → Grass → Mouse", "Mouse → Grass → Hawk → Snake"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Food chains go from producer to consumer: Grass (producer) → Mouse (primary consumer) → Snake (secondary consumer) → Hawk (tertiary consumer). Energy flows from left to right.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS081", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Chemistry", "question_text": "What is the chemical formula for water?", "options": ["HO", "H2O2", "H2O", "OH2"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Water is H2O — two hydrogen atoms bonded to one oxygen atom. H2O2 is hydrogen peroxide. Water's bent molecular shape gives it polarity, which is responsible for many of its unique properties.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS082", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Physics", "question_text": "An object moving in a circular path requires a force directed toward the center of the circle. This force is called:", "options": ["Centrifugal force", "Centripetal force", "Gravitational force", "Normal force"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Centripetal force (meaning 'center-seeking') is directed toward the center of circular motion. Gravity provides the centripetal force for orbiting objects. Centrifugal force is a fictitious outward force.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS083", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "The nervous system transmits signals to and from the brain using:", "options": ["Blood vessels", "Neurons", "Hormones", "Lymph nodes"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Neurons are the specialized cells of the nervous system that transmit electrical signals. The brain and spinal cord form the central nervous system. Hormones are chemical messengers used by the endocrine system.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS084", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "Which of the following is an example of a mutualistic relationship?", "options": ["A lion eating a zebra", "A tapeworm living in a host", "Bees pollinating flowers while collecting nectar", "A cuckoo bird laying eggs in another bird's nest"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Mutualism is when both species benefit. Bees get nectar (food) and flowers get pollinated (reproduction). Predation (lion/zebra) and parasitism (tapeworm, cuckoo) benefit only one organism.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS085", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Chemistry", "question_text": "During electrolysis, water splits into:", "options": ["Carbon dioxide and hydrogen", "Hydrogen and oxygen", "Sodium and chlorine", "Oxygen and carbon"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Electrolysis of water (H2O) splits it into hydrogen gas (H2) at the negative electrode and oxygen gas (O2) at the positive electrode. The ratio is 2:1 hydrogen to oxygen by volume.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS086", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Physics", "question_text": "Which type of simple machine multiplies force by using a wheel rotating on an axle?", "options": ["Pulley", "Lever", "Wheel and axle", "Wedge"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "A wheel and axle multiplies force — turning a large wheel produces greater force at the smaller axle (or vice versa). A steering wheel and screwdriver handle are examples. Pulleys redirect force using rope and wheel.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS087", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "Which macronutrient provides the most energy per gram?", "options": ["Carbohydrates (4 cal/g)", "Protein (4 cal/g)", "Fat (9 cal/g)", "Fiber (2 cal/g)"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Fat provides 9 calories per gram — more than twice the energy of carbohydrates or protein (both 4 cal/g). This is why fat is an efficient long-term energy storage form in the body.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS088", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Earth Science", "question_text": "The process by which plants release water vapor through their leaves is called:", "options": ["Evaporation", "Transpiration", "Condensation", "Respiration"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Transpiration is the release of water vapor from plant leaves through tiny pores called stomata. It is distinct from evaporation (water leaving a surface) and is an important part of the water cycle.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS089", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Chemistry", "question_text": "On the periodic table, elements in the same period (row) have:", "options": ["The same number of valence electrons", "The same number of electron shells (energy levels)", "Similar chemical properties", "The same atomic mass"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 3, "explanation": "Elements in the same period have the same number of electron shells. For example, all period 3 elements have 3 electron shells. Elements in the same group (column) have similar properties due to the same number of valence electrons.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS090", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "What is the role of insulin in the body?", "options": ["Increase blood sugar levels", "Lower blood sugar by allowing cells to absorb glucose", "Digest fats", "Regulate blood pressure"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Insulin, produced by the pancreas, signals cells to absorb glucose from the blood, lowering blood sugar levels. Glucagon does the opposite. Diabetes involves problems with insulin production or response.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS091", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Physics", "question_text": "Which of Newton's laws explains why a rocket accelerates when gases are expelled?", "options": ["First law (inertia)", "Second law (F=ma)", "Third law (action-reaction)", "Law of gravity"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Newton's third law: the rocket expels gas downward (action), and the gas pushes the rocket upward with equal force (reaction). F=ma explains the relationship between force, mass, and acceleration.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS092", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Earth Science", "question_text": "What causes the seasons on Earth?", "options": ["Earth's distance from the Sun changing", "Earth's tilted axis as it orbits the Sun", "The Sun's changing energy output", "The Moon's gravitational pull"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Seasons are caused by Earth's 23.5-degree axial tilt as it orbits the Sun. When a hemisphere tilts toward the Sun it receives more direct sunlight (summer). Earth's distance from the Sun changes very little.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS093", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "Viruses are different from bacteria because viruses:", "options": ["Are larger than bacteria", "Can reproduce on their own", "Are not made of cells and require a host to reproduce", "Can be killed by antibiotics"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Viruses are not cells — they are particles of genetic material (DNA or RNA) in a protein coat. They cannot reproduce without hijacking a host cell. Antibiotics work on bacteria, not viruses.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS094", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Chemistry", "question_text": "A substance that speeds up a chemical reaction without being consumed is called a:", "options": ["Reactant", "Product", "Catalyst", "Solvent"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "A catalyst speeds up a reaction by lowering the activation energy, but is not used up in the process. Enzymes are biological catalysts. Reactants are consumed in reactions. Products are formed.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS095", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Physics", "question_text": "Density is defined as:", "options": ["Mass times volume", "Mass divided by volume", "Volume divided by mass", "Weight divided by area"], "correct_index": 1, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Density = mass ÷ volume (D = m/V). A dense material has a lot of mass packed into a small volume. Water's density is 1 g/cm³ — objects less dense than water float, objects more dense sink.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS096", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Earth Science", "question_text": "What percentage of Earth's surface is covered by water?", "options": ["50%", "60%", "71%", "85%"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "Approximately 71% of Earth's surface is covered by water, mostly the oceans. About 97% of that water is salt water in the oceans, leaving only 3% as fresh water.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS097", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Life Science", "question_text": "The process by which plants make food is called photosynthesis. Plants need all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Carbon dioxide", "Sunlight", "Oxygen", "Water"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Photosynthesis requires CO2, sunlight, and water. Oxygen is a PRODUCT of photosynthesis, not a reactant. The equation: 6CO2 + 6H2O + light → C6H12O6 + 6O2.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS098", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Chemistry", "question_text": "When iron combines with oxygen and water to form rust, this is an example of:", "options": ["A physical change", "Sublimation", "Oxidation", "Condensation"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 2, "explanation": "Rusting is oxidation — iron reacts with oxygen and water to form iron oxide (Fe2O3). It is a chemical change because a new substance (rust) is formed with different properties than the original iron.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
    {"id": "GS099", "section": "General Science", "topic": "Physics", "question_text": "An object at the top of a hill has maximum:", "options": ["Kinetic energy", "Thermal energy", "Potential energy", "Mechanical energy"], "correct_index": 2, "difficulty": 1, "explanation": "At the top of a hill, an object has maximum gravitational potential energy (stored due to height). As it rolls down, PE converts to kinetic energy (energy of motion). At the bottom, KE is maximum.", "test_types": ["ASVAB"]},
